WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.140
Hi, everybody. I'm Tesla Dubois, and I'm really excited to be here today to tell you all about

00:00:13.140 --> 00:00:20.559
solving a secure geocoding problem that hardly anybody has. So you might think from the title

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:26.719
of my talk that I'm someone who's overly concerned with the precise locations of things. But

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:32.360
in reality, I place a lot more value on the journey. So today, I'm going to tell you about

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:38.680
my journey of getting from one place in data science learning to another place that was

00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:46.400
relatively further along through the task of creating a secure, code-free geocoder.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:52.080
So first of all, why build a secure, code-free geocoder? Well, as my puppy is proudly telling

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:57.400
you here, I work at Fox Chase Cancer Center, and I'm a geospatial data analyst there. So

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:03.599
I do things like this. I characterize cancer burden by neighborhood. This is in Philadelphia,

00:01:03.599 --> 00:01:08.400
and in this case, looking at lung cancer. Then I do the same thing with cancer risk.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:13.160
So in this case, we're looking at smoking behavior and the density of tobacco retailers.

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:17.959
And then I use that to inform interventions. In this case, we're looking at tobacco treatment

00:01:17.959 --> 00:01:24.800
participants for our smoking cessation program. Basically, I'm arguing that targeted cancer

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:31.559
prevention efforts depend on geocoded patient data. So geocoding is the process of turning

00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:38.879
a text address into a geographically referenced coordinate system like latitude and longitude.

00:01:38.879 --> 00:01:44.239
And there are many ways to do this. Most people can use one of these tools. But the thing

00:01:44.239 --> 00:01:49.919
about doing this with patient data is that you have to be really careful because an address

00:01:49.919 --> 00:01:55.800
is an individual identifier. So we can't send that over a server. At least the most conservative

00:01:55.800 --> 00:02:00.959
health researchers are not going to send that over a server for data security concerns.

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:07.599
There are a few options that are secure for geocoding, but they tend to be clunky, expensive,

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:14.880
and or require coding. So this is a data science conference. Why is coding an issue here?

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:20.399
Well, while I am the only geospatial analyst at Fox Chase Cancer Center, I'm not the only

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:27.080
one interested in using geocoded data. Normally, the next step after geocoding is that we link

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:32.039
the geocodes with some area-level measures of social determinants of health, which can

00:02:32.039 --> 00:02:38.479
be defined as the environments in which we live, work, and play. So I'm going to give

00:02:38.479 --> 00:02:44.399
you a few examples of other folks at Fox Chase who are interested in using this type of data.

00:02:44.399 --> 00:02:50.000
We have clinical researchers who want to know whether socioeconomic status has any association

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:55.720
with treatment outcomes in their patients. We have a multidisciplinary team right now

00:02:55.720 --> 00:03:01.479
who's working on increasing diversity in our clinical trials and want help with focusing

00:03:01.479 --> 00:03:06.360
their recruitment and education programs and which community partners we should engage

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:11.259
in this effort. We have leaders of cancer prevention and control interventions like

00:03:11.259 --> 00:03:16.039
our mobile mammography unit and our patient navigation programs who want to make sure

00:03:16.039 --> 00:03:23.279
we're prioritizing and serving residents in the highest risk areas. And finally, our leaders

00:03:23.279 --> 00:03:28.119
and administrators of the Cancer Center are required to report back to the National Cancer

00:03:28.199 --> 00:03:33.520
Institute how well we're serving the residents in our designated catchment area, whether

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:38.839
they're representative, our patients are representative of that catchment area, and how we're addressing

00:03:38.839 --> 00:03:45.839
disparities. So currently what happens is that these types

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:52.160
of inquiries go to my fantastic boss, and then they're passed on to me like data requests.

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:56.759
And on one hand, it's really awesome that I get to support this really impactful work

00:03:56.759 --> 00:04:03.399
at Fox Chase. And I also got to thinking that if I could give researchers and administrators

00:04:03.399 --> 00:04:10.360
at Fox Chase a tool to be a bit more independent in geocoding and potentially linking that

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:18.000
patient data with common measures from area-level measures, that I would be freed up to do some

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.480
of the more advanced spatial analyses that I'm interested in, like when I presented this

00:04:23.799 --> 00:04:29.160
machine learning project that I did on early-onset colorectal cancer.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:35.640
So I wanted to create a code-free, secure geocoding application for researchers and

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:40.799
administrators working with patient data. And I actually workshopped this idea quite

00:04:40.799 --> 00:04:47.040
a bit with my fantastic boss, Dr. Shannon Lynch, and her collaborator, Dr. Kevin Henry.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.040
And actually, because of those two individuals, I'm going back to school now for my Ph.D.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:57.880
in Geography. Thank you.

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:04.040
So I took a class last semester on geospatial application development, and it was a project-based

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:07.880
class. We had to be in group projects. And I presented this as an idea on the first day

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:13.799
of class. And quickly, two of my classmates joined my group. So we sat in the back of

00:05:13.799 --> 00:05:17.519
the classroom while other groups were forming, and I talked about my ideas for how we would

00:05:17.519 --> 00:05:23.200
approach this in R. And right before we left the classroom, the professor told us that

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:33.559
we had to use Python-based solutions. So this is where I need to tell you that I've always

00:05:33.559 --> 00:05:41.920
been a bit of a rebel. And in fact, as this newspaper clip tells you, I was the only girl

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:46.720
in my all-girls private Catholic high school who rode a motorcycle from a different county

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:51.519
to school every day. And what the newspaper doesn't tell you is that on my lunch break,

00:05:51.519 --> 00:05:56.399
I used to get back on my motorcycle and ride through the convent behind the school and

00:05:56.399 --> 00:06:02.000
through the paved rose gardens and wait for the nuns to come out and yell at me.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:08.679
So when my professor told me, an R lover, that I had to use Python-based solution, I

00:06:08.679 --> 00:06:17.640
immediately went home and started coding it up in R. So I will argue that this wasn't

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:24.519
just an act of rebellion. I just as in my teenagerhood, I really needed to explore the

00:06:24.519 --> 00:06:31.679
world in a mode that felt freeing to me and assert myself as an independent being. Similarly,

00:06:31.679 --> 00:06:39.359
in this project, I needed to deeply understand conceptually what I was trying to do in a

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:46.559
language that I understood and knew well. So the first phase of this project is do you

00:06:46.559 --> 00:06:52.320
build understanding with tools that you know? This is what it looked like for me in R. I

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:58.600
started with an address, and then I used the Tigris package to pull down all of the streets

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:04.519
for that county within which the address resided. And this is important because this

00:07:04.519 --> 00:07:10.279
county is the only information that I sent to a remote server, and that's not individually

00:07:10.279 --> 00:07:17.239
identifiable information. From there, I used dplyr to filter down to the correct zip code,

00:07:17.239 --> 00:07:23.480
stringer to match on street name, dplyr again to get down to the line segment that included

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:31.600
the number of the address. And then I took the centroid of that final line segment using

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:38.600
SF. And this is a crude geocode, but I would argue at least in an urban setting, it's sufficient.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:45.119
Next I can use tidy census to pull in the census tracts again and link it spatially

00:07:45.119 --> 00:07:52.880
to that point. And tidy census again to pull in area level measures of interest. And then

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:59.200
I do everybody's favorite. Oh, sorry. Then I have this result, which is an address with

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:04.959
the latitude and longitude and a linked area level measure of interest. Then I do everybody's

00:08:04.959 --> 00:08:12.480
favorite and stick it in a for loop. And this was my R geocoder. As I iterate over addresses,

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:20.600
I'm getting a bigger data frame with all the linked data. So while this worked, there were

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:27.799
several problems with this. First, addresses had to be an exact match. So if there wasn't a W for

00:08:27.799 --> 00:08:32.679
West Main Street, there just wouldn't be a match at all. There was no name regularization built

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:37.559
into this. I could have done it. I didn't do it. Second, my R environment got way too big,

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:42.960
way too fast. If I was including multiple counties in that initial data set, I'm pulling down those

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:48.880
line files, which are really big for every single county, and it starts to get bogged down. Third,

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:53.599
this is definitely not code free. It worked for me, but it wasn't something I could extend to

00:08:53.599 --> 00:09:00.719
the other researchers and administrators at Fox Chase. And fourth, it wasn't a Python-based

00:09:00.719 --> 00:09:05.799
solution. And we did for a moment consider just translating it to Python and turning it in,

00:09:05.799 --> 00:09:15.719
but the other three issues would have still remained. So if my teens were characterized by

00:09:15.719 --> 00:09:21.400
riding a motorcycle through the convent, then my 20s were characterized by trying to shove my

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:29.239
triathlon bike into the back of my Mini Cooper. So in my 20s, I was really into triathlons. I'd

00:09:29.239 --> 00:09:35.280
finally gotten to four-wheeled vehicle after moving out to the East Coast, and I would spend

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:40.200
my Sundays driving my bike out to a place where I could ride for 50 miles at a time with very little

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:46.760
car traffic, and then I'd get back to my car, and inevitably I'd be hot and tired and dehydrated,

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:52.760
and I'd have a hard time fitting my bike back into the Mini Cooper. So I would call my husband

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:58.840
and tell him, first of all, like, I'm done with my ride, I survived, and then talk to him as I

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:03.119
tried shoving the bike into the Mini Cooper, and I'd tell him what I was trying. You know,

00:10:03.119 --> 00:10:08.840
I put the other seat down, I took the front wheel off, and he might suggest something like,

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:13.919
why don't you try putting it rear wheel first, or, you know, and sometimes that would help,

00:10:13.919 --> 00:10:21.039
but usually just the process of me talking about what I was trying would give me an idea of what

00:10:21.039 --> 00:10:27.640
to try next, and eventually I'd get the back of the Mini Cooper shut, and I'd be on my way. So

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:34.080
this next phase of the building a code-free geocoder was very similar to that. We had a

00:10:34.159 --> 00:10:39.840
lot of tools that we ended up using, and on my team none of us had any experience with any of

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:45.599
these before we started. So we started out by just like going home, each picking one, trying

00:10:45.599 --> 00:10:50.159
to become an expert on it, coming back, talking to each other about what we learned, and then

00:10:50.159 --> 00:10:57.559
slowly starting to puzzle these different things together. So that's the next phase, using the

00:10:57.559 --> 00:11:06.119
talk-try method to iteratively puzzle new tools together. We started out with this tutorial by

00:11:06.119 --> 00:11:11.239
Michelle Tobias, which I appreciated both for the technical expertise, but also for the validation

00:11:11.239 --> 00:11:19.200
that this was really hard, and confusing, and took a long time. And even with that tutorial, we spent

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:26.239
many nights on Zoom looking at pages of failure messages, but eventually we did come up with

00:11:26.239 --> 00:11:33.200
something that worked, and this is how it worked. So first, we have a shell script that starts a

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:38.719
Docker container. You have to have Docker Desktop already installed on your computer, but it doesn't

00:11:38.719 --> 00:11:44.239
need to be open or running. The shell script will start the Docker container and put a Postgres SQL

00:11:44.239 --> 00:11:50.159
database on it. Then we have another shell script that will pull the relevant line files with

00:11:50.159 --> 00:11:58.239
Postgres and store them on that Postgres SQL database. And this screenshot here is hard to see, but we

00:11:58.239 --> 00:12:04.320
have a file in there that updates every time you pull new county line files, so that the next time

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:09.679
you run it, you don't pull those same county line files again, and the data persists in your Docker

00:12:09.679 --> 00:12:16.280
database. And again, this is the only information that we're sending to a remote server, is the

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:24.119
county. Next, we have Postgres functions to geocode against the database. So Postgres has a geocoding

00:12:24.119 --> 00:12:30.359
function already, and it normally sends the address over a server, but instead we're using our Docker

00:12:30.359 --> 00:12:36.039
database as the server. So we're directing the data to our local Docker database, and it's never going

00:12:36.039 --> 00:12:43.400
over a server. So we are coding this up with a Python function. And finally, we created an interface

00:12:43.400 --> 00:12:49.479
with QtDesigner and linked the whole thing up with Python. And this is a very basic, basic user

00:12:49.479 --> 00:12:56.280
interface, but it does have a couple options. You can name your input file, designate your output file,

00:12:56.280 --> 00:13:01.719
and then you can pick between having your output be a CSV or a shapefile. You can choose to have

00:13:01.719 --> 00:13:08.599
your points jittered, which means just randomly moved within certain bounds from the true

00:13:08.679 --> 00:13:15.000
latitude and longitude. And then you could add the social determinants of health data at the census

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:23.960
track level or not. Okay, so if my teens were characterized by riding a motorcycle through the

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:30.760
convent, and my 20s were characterized by shoving a bicycle into the back of the Mini Cooper, my 30s,

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:37.719
how many people have experienced their 30s in here? Okay, all right. So my 30s have been characterized

00:13:37.719 --> 00:13:46.039
by a bit of compromise. So when I was pregnant with my second daughter, my husband and I decided

00:13:46.039 --> 00:13:52.280
it was time to give up on any idea that we would ever be cool again, and we went ahead and bought

00:13:52.280 --> 00:14:00.039
a minivan. It was very sad. We had to let go of some ego, but it was the most functional choice,

00:14:00.039 --> 00:14:05.799
you know? It would work for our family. But I believe that you should really own where you are

00:14:05.799 --> 00:14:12.039
when you have to make that type of decision. So we went ahead and got the license plate, van,

00:14:12.039 --> 00:14:19.880
with five A's. And the only time that has backfired is when my kid got a point off on a spelling test

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:25.159
for putting too many A's in the word van in first grade. And she tells me it was a joke, but the

00:14:25.159 --> 00:14:30.919
teacher obviously didn't get it. But she only put four A's, so she was right to get a point off.

00:14:31.159 --> 00:14:39.479
So this phase of this project also required some compromise, and we'll get to that.

00:14:40.599 --> 00:14:46.919
But in doing so, I had to, you know, prioritize functionality over flair, much like getting the

00:14:46.919 --> 00:14:52.599
minivan. But before we had to compromise, we were actually feeling quite good about where we were.

00:14:52.599 --> 00:14:57.799
So one week before the final was due, we gave a demo to our class. I'm going to walk you through

00:14:57.799 --> 00:15:05.159
that now. So the first demo, we're exporting a CSV of true points with the census track variables

00:15:05.159 --> 00:15:11.400
attached. Now, this might be a little hard to see, but we're starting down here with a CSV that has

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:17.960
two columns. One is just an address ID, and the other one is the addresses all in one column.

00:15:17.960 --> 00:15:24.599
And we hadn't packaged this into an executable file yet, so we're pressing run right up here from

00:15:24.599 --> 00:15:30.840
the Spyder interface, and then it pops open our GUI. We can navigate to the CSV of addresses,

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:36.520
designate our output. We want a CSV, not jittered, with the social determinants of health data at

00:15:36.520 --> 00:15:43.880
census track level. Press OK, and it gives us this output that it's telling us that it's pulling

00:15:43.880 --> 00:15:51.159
those county line files. And then we have the file pop-up where we designated. We can open this up,

00:15:51.159 --> 00:15:57.159
and we see that we do indeed have a latitude and longitude, and importantly, that rating for how

00:15:57.159 --> 00:16:03.400
good of a match it is. So I have a PO box in here as a test. It has a really poor rating, and that's

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:08.440
what we want to see. And then we have the area level social determinants of health measures on

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:15.080
there. In our second demo, we have a shapefile of jittered points and the census track variables

00:16:15.080 --> 00:16:22.039
attached. Again, we're going to go ahead and press run, put in our file, designate the output. We want

00:16:22.039 --> 00:16:27.640
a shapefile. We do want it jittered this time, and again, we're attaching the census track variables.

00:16:27.640 --> 00:16:32.919
Press run. This time, it's not pulling those county line files because we already did it

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:37.320
two minutes ago. And remember, the data persists in our Docker container, so it doesn't have to

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:42.119
call it again. This time, it's telling us that it has to shorten the column names when it's

00:16:42.119 --> 00:16:48.119
exporting a shapefile, which if you do geospatial stuff, you're familiar with. Not a big deal. We can

00:16:48.119 --> 00:16:55.080
open up QGIS now, call in that shapefile, and indeed, we see that that jittered point is just

00:16:55.080 --> 00:17:01.080
slightly off from the true latitude and longitude. All right, so we were feeling pretty good. Our

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:05.479
professor was impressed. Our classmates were impressed. We thought we were pretty awesome,

00:17:06.119 --> 00:17:12.119
but then we still had to package it up into a downloadable executable that somebody could click

00:17:12.119 --> 00:17:18.920
on their desktop and it would pop open our GUI, and we ran into some problems. So this is our

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:26.040
group chat the day before the final was due, and it turned out that the Python module that I was

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:31.800
using to calculate the census track level variables was causing an issue when we were packaging it

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:38.520
into an executable, so I had to just comment out all of that code and say, okay, well, we're not

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:44.040
turning in, you know, that. That was like a nice to have, right? Then we did get it into an executable

