file, but it wouldn't run when you double-clicked on it from download. It would only run if you go

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:54.359
to the terminal and tell it to run from the terminal, which is not entirely code-free.

00:17:55.160 --> 00:18:02.199
But the final was due, and we had to turn in what we had, and so that's what we did. We turned it in,

00:18:02.199 --> 00:18:09.719
and this is where being a journey person really comes in handy, right? Because even though I

00:18:09.719 --> 00:18:16.040
didn't get all the way where I wanted to get with this geocoder, I would argue that by building

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:21.479
conceptual understanding with tools that I knew well, using the talk-try method to iteratively

00:18:21.479 --> 00:18:26.760
experiment and puzzle things together, and knowing when it's time to compromise, and by doing so,

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:33.319
prioritizing functionality over flair, I definitely progressed in my data science learning journey.

00:18:33.319 --> 00:18:38.280
And not only did I progress in that journey, even though it's not ready for prime time, I did create

00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:45.239
something that I can use at work. So I recently geocoded 3,000 patient addresses. 85% of them

00:18:45.239 --> 00:18:50.680
were geocoded with the Python-based solution, which is pretty good. Like, it's what you would

